  "prompt": "In blood transfusion what is major, minor cross match and the purpose of it?",
  "response": "In blood transfusion, major and minor crossmatching are essential compatibility tests performed to ensure safe blood transfusion by detecting potential antibody-antigen reactions.\n\nMajor Crossmatch:\n- Recipient's serum is mixed with donor's red blood cells\n- Purpose:\n  1. Detect any antibodies in recipient's plasma against donor's RBC antigens\n  2. Prevent potentially fatal hemolytic transfusion reactions\n  3. Identify incompatible blood units\n- Checks for potential agglutination or hemolysis\n- Most critical crossmatch test\n\nMinor Crossmatch:\n- Donor's serum is mixed with recipient's red blood cells\n- Purpose:\n  1. Identify recipient's antibodies in donor's plasma\n  2. Detect potential antibodies that might cause hemolysis\n  3. Ensure plasma compatibility\n- Less critical than major crossmatch\n- Often performed alongside major crossmatch\n\nAdditional details:\n- Both tests are typically performed before blood transfusion\n- Help prevent transfusion-related complications\n- Crucial in identifying blood type compatibility\n- Reduce risk of adverse transfusion reactions\n\nThese crossmatching procedures are essential for ensuring patient safety during blood transfusions.",
